                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Probably rebound Bushehr former owner <persName role="fmo ins ato"
                              key="person_f6703">Edward Galley</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn, unsupported, with edges trimmed and endbands likely twined at
                              <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail"
                              to="Tail">tail</locus>, now lost. Covered in full maroon goatskin
                              <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material>,
                           flush-cut, with a flap, and defined joints (Type II binding per
                           Déroche).</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Boards decorated with recessed central scalloped
                           mandorlas with detached pendants blocked in silver, now tarnished, and
                           cornerpieces and cornerpieces of black shagreen leather. All bear
                           brightly hand-painted flowers and foliage, known as <hi rend="italic"
                              >mīnāyī</hi> (enamelled) due to the shiny appearance of the paint. For
                           another example held in the Rylands, see <ref
                              target="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/view/MS-PERSIAN-00037/"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 37</idno></ref>. See also Mihan as well as Bayānī and Ardakānī on this style.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>341</height>
                              <width>219</width>
                              <depth>54</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. Tight sewing restricts opening to
                           the gutter margins. Endbands missing.</condition>
