               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high" type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089" key="place_6005089">Safavid
                        Empire</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1598">1007 AH (1598
                     CE)</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently owned or inspected by at least four individuals: one
                        whose immolated seal impression appears on page <locus from="1" to="1"
                           >1</locus>, another who wrote a biographical account of the author
                        adjacent to a seal impression bearing the name of <persName
                           role="seal ins fmo">Muḥammad ‘Alī</persName>, as well as two other seal
                        impressions on page <locus from="202" to="202">202a</locus>, including one
                        dated <date>1107 AH (1695–96 CE)</date> that mentions Safavid ruler Sulaymān
                        I (b. 1648, r. 1666–1694), and another referencing Fatḥ ‘Alī Shāh Qājār (b.
                        1772, r. 1797–1834).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Later acquired by by <persName type="standard" role="fmo ato seal"
                           key="person_f6703">Edward Galley (ca. 1750–1804)</persName>, <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/239176400">East India Company</orgName>
                        Resident at <placeName>Bushire (Bushehr), Iran</placeName> between <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" from="1780" to="1787">1780 to 1787</date>, where he
                        possibly aquired this volume. Ultimately Collector-General of
                           <placeName>Surat, India</placeName> where he passed away, Galley's
                        executors subsequently sold his library there; however, the identity of the
                        purchaser and circumstances of the volume's arrival in Britain remain
                        unclear (see Robinson, p. 209).</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Probably the same manuscript listed by <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName>
                        bookseller <persName role="bsl" cert="high"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/12688740" key="person_12688740">Henry George
                           Bohn (1796–1884)</persName> in his <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1841">1841</date> catalogue, no. 13618, described as <quote
                           xml:lang="en">...poems on the Soofy, or mystical doctrines of the
                           Persians" which comports with the note in Galley's hand on <locus
                              from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">left doublure</locus> in
                           double columns, on 610 pages of very stout paper, highly glazed. The
                           first three pages are adorned with very curious and early illuminations,
                           native binding, 2£ 12s 6d.</quote>
                     </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Possibly purchased from Bohn by orientalist <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes (1798–1868)</persName> acquired
                        it from an unidentified source. Ultimately appointed <orgName>King's
                           College</orgName> Professor of Oriental Languages, Forbes described this
                        volume in his <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date> catalogue,
                        valued at £8 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi> (also inscribed on the <locus
                           from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">right pastedown</locus>),
                        before he sold his manuscript collection to his publisher <orgName
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"
                              ><persName key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl"
                              change="#prov-markup">W. H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> in
                        exchange for an annuity.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently sold by <orgName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"><persName
                              key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl" change="#prov-markup">W.
                              H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> to <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date> for his Bibliotheca Lindesiana at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
